The paper deals with session-based recommendation models, which are a subfield of machine learning and artificial intelligence. The use of graph neural networks (GNNs) to model session data suggests a focus on learning representations, which is a common theme in the subfield of deep learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the issue of popularity bias, which is a common problem in information retrieval (cs.IR) and recommendation systems (cs.AI). The proposed solution involves normalizing the learned representations, which is a technique that has been used in various subfields of machine learning, including social influence analysis (cs.SI) and natural language processing (cs.CL). Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG, cs.IR, cs.AI, cs.SI, and cs.CL, in that order.
